snippet: A former corporate lawyer has a radical proposal for curbing corporate America’s excesses, even if it means more legal fights for his onetime clients.
lead_paragraph: Good Tuesday morning. The big news today: Capital One’s large data breach. More on that below. (Was this email forwarded to you? Sign up here.)
abstract: A former corporate lawyer has a radical proposal for curbing corporate America’s excesses, even if it means more legal fights for his onetime clients.

snippet: A national campaign has exposed each and every one of his weaknesses. Is there any chance of a comeback?
lead_paragraph: It’s got to be hard to be Beto O’Rourke these days. Preparing for the Democratic debate on Tuesday night, he must feel as if he’s been shipped to an alternate universe, like when Superman found himself trapped in Bizarroworld, where everything was the same but completely different.

headline_main: Democratic Debate, Capital One, Baltimore: Your Tuesday Briefing

snippet: Yes, the two-night, 20-candidate format is ludicrous, but can we please have a reasonable debate about America’s future?
lead_paragraph: Gail Collins: O.K., Bret, it’s debate week — Round 2. Are you still rooting for Mayor Pete?
abstract: Yes, the two-night, 20-candidate format is ludicrous, but can we please have a reasonable debate about America’s future?

snippet: In a key swing state, Democrats looking at the presidential field were more likely to follow their head than their heart in whom to support.
lead_paragraph: NEWTOWN, Pa. — Diane LeBas, a 71-year-old substitute teacher attending the Newtown Democrats’ summer picnic on Sunday, recounted how she was tear-gassed protesting the Vietnam War. No one could question her progressivism.
abstract: In a key swing state, Democrats looking at the presidential field were more likely to follow their head than their heart in whom to support.

snippet: Joe Biden is in the hot seat.
lead_paragraph: It’s crunchtime for the Democratic presidential candidates. The second set of debates will air live from Detroit on Tuesday and Wednesday — with 20 contenders split evenly between the two nights — and the four-hour spectacle is being pitched as an elimination round worthy of “The Bachelorette.” The debates scheduled for September and October have a higher threshold for participation in terms of poll numbers and campaign donations, which means that, among the more marginal candidates, those who fail to distinguish themselves in this showdown might not get another shot.
abstract: Joe Biden is in the hot seat.
